history.text: Have you seen the movie Dunkirk?
Yes
Did you enjoy it?
I didn't realize that portions of the movie were actually filmed on location in Dunkirk
It was a very suspenseful movie.
I didn't realize that either.  I guess they also filmed part of it in Los Angeles as well.
Yeah the information we've been given makes it sound like the ending was filmed in LA. Wonder if it was all on a sound stage?
I wouldn't mind seeing a sequel to find out what happened to Tom Hardy's character after he gets captured by the Germans at the end.
I wouldn't either.  Not certain they will do a sequel or not.  If they do I would like to see it.
I haven't heard anything about any sequel so probably not. But it was a bit of a cliffhanger ending. I could see a sequel being really similar to saving private ryan. Saving Pilot Hardy lol
True.
hmm ok new paragraph to discuss. The moonstone boat sequence where the soldier ends up blinding and then killing the boy.
I can't imagine being in Tommy's shoes as the sole survivor of an ambush like that.
oh was he the private from the opening sequence?
Yes.
Yeah they were totally outgunned in that opening. Looked like a bunch of Lee Enfield bolt action rifles against Germans with stg44's
I didn't realize the french still had some defensive formations in the area, that kind of saved him
I didn't realize that either.
Gibson
What a horrible military blunder on the part of the British though. Basically their entire ground force cut off and left out to die without an exit plan.
Yes it is not good to not have an exit plan.
Especially since they sent the majority of their troops. They were all in right off the bat. Probably why most military actions start off with expeditionary forces now.
I can't imagine Tommy and Alex's reacton after finding out Gibson was a spy.
was he a spy or just a french soldier pretending to be british to survive?
Either way he lied about his true identity.  I guess if you put yourself in his shoes, he did what he had to to try to survive.
Yeah he was going to do whatever he had to to get off that beach
kind of follows what they had been doing though, with trying to sneak on board that initial ship with the stretcher that had a dead soldier on it
really it was all pretty insane to see all those soldiers just standing in formation out in the open on the beach
like shooting ducks in a barrel
Yes.  At the beach when Commander Bolton watched the last British soldiers leave. He confirms that 300,000 have been evacuated. That was ten times more than they estimated.
yeah and accomplished mostly with small private vessels across a straight full of uboats and enemy planes

Yes.  It is amazing they were able to accomplish that with small private vessels.  
Thankful that George was able to be recognized as a hero.
At least his death didn't feel quite as painful since he was recognized.
oh yeah that's right! Forgot about that part
Some consolation for his parents I'm sure
Alex also received a hero's welcome instead of being publicly scorned as he feared.  Such a good movie.
Winston Churchill also wrote an address to the nation in the newspaper.  I am sure Tommy enjoyed reading that.

yeah that's true, he was worried about that when he arrived back home. I think the british realized they were lucky to have gotten their soldiers back, that it wasn't a total loss or failure but represented hope that they could still defend their country
Yes.
